\begin_layout Section*
Theoretical Framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are interested in the short-run effects of increases in minimum wages
 on a ZIP code's rental market.
 Residents in this ZIP code potentially work in some other ZIP code, under
 a different minimum wage policy.
 We let 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathcal{Z}_{i}$
\end_inset

 be workplaces of residents of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{w}_{i}$
\end_inset

 be the MW binding at ZIP code 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula ${\underline{w}_{z}}_{z\in\mathcal{Z}_{i}}$
\end_inset

 the ones binding at each workplace.
 Residents of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 meet in a single market to rent square feet, with equilibrium rents per
 square foot 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{z\in\mathcal{Z}_{i}}L_{iz}h_{iz}(r_{i},p_{i},y_{z})=D_{i}(r_{i}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{z}$
\end_inset

 are prices of local consumption goods, and income of people working in
 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula ${L_{iz}}_{z\in\mathcal{Z}_{i}}$
\end_inset

 are (exogenous) measures of workers commuting to 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $L_{i}=\sum_{z\in\mathcal{Z}_{i}}L_{iz}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's residents), and 
\begin_inset Formula ${h_{iz}(\cdot)}_{z\in\mathcal{Z}_{i}}$
\end_inset

 are housing demand functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=p_{i}(\underline{w}_{i})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{z}=y_{z}(\underline{w}_{z})$
\end_inset

, both increasing, we can use the equilibrium condition to write a change
 in the log of rents as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\ln r_{i}=\gamma_{i}d\ln\underline{w}_{i}+\beta_{i}\sum_{z\in\mathcal{Z}_{i}}\pi_{iz}d\ln\underline{w}_{z}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

 are parameters that depend on elasticities, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{iz}=L_{iz}/L_{i}$
\end_inset

 are commuting shares.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We also need to assume that the elasticity of housing demand to income doesn't
 vary by 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It turns out that, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial h_{iz}/\partial p_{i}<0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial h_{iz}/\partial y_{z}>0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}<0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a result of this exercise, we expect workplace and residence MW changes
 to have opposing effects on rental prices.
\end_layout

