\begin_layout Section*
Empirical Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are interested in models of the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ln r_{it}=\alpha_{i}+\tilde{\delta}_{t}+\gamma\ln\underline{w}_{it}+\beta\underline{w}_{it}^{exp}+\epsilon_{it}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is ZIP code and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is monthly data.
 We sometimes include time-varying covariates or allow time effects to vary
 by some wider geography (state, CBSA).
 Taking first differences, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\ln r_{it}=\delta_{t}+\gamma\Delta\ln\underline{w}_{it}+\beta\Delta\underline{w}_{it}^{exp}+\Delta\epsilon_{it}\label{eq:fd_model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{t}=\tilde{\delta}_{t}-\tilde{\delta}_{t-1}.$
\end_inset

 We use a first-differences specification because we expect the unobserved
 shocks in the levels equation to be positively correlated over time.
 Furtermore, we detected strong correlation of local rents over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimate this model under an unbalanced, partially balanced and fully
 balanced panels of the Zillow rents data and we consistently obtain negative
 estimates for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and positive ones for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
